        <chunk>
          <text>
            Florence's return to the common area creates immediate tension.

            Holloway's fruiting bodies contract when they see her — Runner's vines coil tight, Remedy's edges pull back, and the room temperature drops about ten degrees — metaphorically, but it feels literal.

            Holloway says,
            "Florence."

            Florence replies,
            "Holloway."

            I announce,
            "Kira brought Florence to help with tactical defense — because we need tactical defense and Florence knows how to coordinate it."

            Remedy starts,
            "We don't—"

            The eastern wall explodes. Not literally — a section of it bursts inward as hostile roots punch through, thick and aggressive and very much not friendly. They spread across the floor like grabbing hands, seeking purchase, seeking to tear more structure apart.

            Scout's bounce is pure alarm.
            *"ATTACK!"*

            ¶

            And then everything happens at once.

            More roots burst through the western wall, then the southern wall. Hostile plants hit us from three directions simultaneously — a coordinated assault, exactly like Florence predicted.

            Through the breaches I can see them: masses of plant life advancing with purpose. Some are tall and thorny, others are low-spreading and toxic-looking. Bioluminescent signals flash between them — communication, coordination. This is organized warfare.

            "Defensive positions!" Holloway shouts, but it's unclear what positions those are.

            Runner dives underground, their vines disappearing into the floor — fighting the hostile roots on their own territory. Remedy spreads toward the western breach, releasing clouds of something sharp and chemical-smelling. Velvet's offshoots rush to reinforce the damaged walls, growing rapidly to seal breaches.

            But it's all reactive — no strategy. Just defend what's nearest and hope.

            A spore cloud drifts through the eastern breach — thick, yellowish, definitely toxic, moving with purpose and seeking targets.

            Holloway warns,
            "Kira, get back!"

            I scramble backward as the cloud drifts past where I was standing. Where it touches the floor, the moss withers. Okay, that's genuinely dangerous.

            Scout bounces between me and the cloud — tiny but fierce, ready to protect. I grab them and pull them back —
            "Scout, no — you can't fight poison!"

            More hostile roots punch through the floor. Runner is down there somewhere, fighting them, but there are too many. The hostile roots are spreading everywhere, tearing up the facility's foundation.

            A section of ceiling collapses, structural integrity failing as roots destabilize everything.

            Holloway tries to coordinate —
            "Velvet, reinforce above — Remedy, counter those spores — Runner, can you—"

            Another wall section gives way as a massive, thorny hostile plant pushes through, radiating aggression. It's hard to tell where one hostile plant ends and another begins; they might all be connected, one vast organism attacking as coordinated units.
          </text>
