        <chunk>
          <text>
            The thorny one sends out barbs—actual projectile thorns that embed in the walls and the floor—one narrowly missing my head.

            I duck behind a structural pillar and exclaim:
            "*OKAY, that's terrifying!*"

            Buddy pipes up in my mind:
            "Kira, your heart rate is extremely elevated! Perhaps you should—"

            I snap:
            "Not now, Buddy!"

            Buddy replies in my head:
            "Of course! Survival first!"

            Remedy's chemical cloud meets the hostile spore cloud mid-air—they react, fizzing and bubbling and creating a third substance that's probably also toxic. Great—now we have competing poison clouds.

            Holloway asks:
            "Remedy, what is that?"

            Remedy calls back—
            "Neutralization reaction! —Should render both clouds inert!"

            Holloway, skeptical, says:
            "Should?"

            Remedy answers:
            "Probably! Chemistry isn't always predictable!"

            The resulting cloud settles to the floor as a thick sludge—better than airborne poison, but now we have toxic sludge everywhere. I make a mental note: avoid the sludge.

            ¶

            Underground, something crashes and the floor shakes. Runner's vines burst up through a weak point, wrapped around hostile roots—both plants grappling for dominance. It's like watching an underground wrestling match.

            Holloway shouts down:
            "Runner, status?"

            Runner reports—
            "Engaged! —Multiple hostiles! —Underground network is extensive!"

            More bioluminescent flashing from the hostile plants outside—signals, commands, tactical updates. They're communicating better than we are. They have a plan.

            Velvet seals one breach just as another opens; they're spreading too thin, trying to reinforce too many weak points at once. A hostile plant sends out creeping vines that corrode whatever they touch—Velvet has to pull back or get dissolved.

            I yell to Holloway:
            "We need to concentrate defense! —We can't protect everything!"

            Holloway asks, desperate:
            "What do we abandon?"

            I don't know—it's Florence's kind of decision. Florence stands near the center, watching everything with professional frustration, watching us lose because we don't know what we're doing.

            A root wraps around my ankle. I yelp and try to pull free, but it's strong—it's dragging me toward the eastern breach and the mass of hostile plants outside.

            Scout attacks the root, bouncing hard and trying to break it. It doesn't break.

            I shout, *"RUNNER!"*

            Runner's vines shoot up from underground and sever the hostile root; it releases me and withers back. I scramble away from the breach.

            I gasp, "Thanks!"

            Runner advises before diving back underground:
            "Stay away from openings!"

            Yeah—good plan. Except openings are appearing everywhere.

            The northern wall, previously untouched, suddenly sprouts hostile growth—they were making us think the north was safe. Now they're hitting all four sides. We're surrounded.

            Remedy states the obvious—
            "This isn't working! —We're losing ground!"

            Holloway orders, voice edged with desperation:
            "Keep fighting!"
          </text>
