        <chunk>
          <text>
            Velvet abandons trying to seal the breaches and instead grows a defensive barrier around the facility's core — protecting essential systems: life support and medical equipment. It's smart prioritization, but it means giving up the outer areas.

            We're contracting — losing space; the hostile plants are winning.

            A massive thorny branch punches through the western wall, narrowly missing Remedy. Remedy deploys more defensive chemicals but is running low — you can only produce so many compounds before exhausting resources.

            Scout stays close to me — bouncing, alert for any new threats. Scout is scared but trying so hard to be brave.

            The floor cracks from more underground fighting. Runner surfaces briefly — vines torn, sap leaking; they're injured — then dives back down because there's no choice: the underground assault continues.

            I tell Holloway —
            "Runner's hurt!"

            Holloway — overwhelmed —
            "I know! I know — but we need them down there or hostile roots will destabilize the entire foundation!"

            A spore cloud — darker than the first, probably more toxic — drifts through the southern breach. Remedy doesn't have the resources to counter it. The cloud settles over part of Velvet's defensive barrier; Velvet's growth withers where it touches.

            Multiple plants shout —
            *VELVET!*

            Velvet calls back — pained —
            "I'm okay! Just damaged, not destroyed!"

            The facility is falling apart around us — walls breached on all sides, floors unstable, ceiling sections collapsed. We're fighting hard, but we're not winning — not even close.

            ¶

            And the hostile plants keep coming.

            Holloway tries to coordinate —
            "Remedy, focus on the western breach!"
            "Velvet, prioritize core systems!"
            "Runner, if you can disrupt their underground network —"

            But it's still reactive — still responding to immediate threats without any overall strategy. We're playing defense while they execute a plan.

            Another projectile thorn nearly hits me. I'm pressed against a pillar — Scout guarding me — watching our home get destroyed because we can't coordinate effectively.

            Florence hasn't moved — still watching and analyzing, seeing exactly how badly we're failing.

            Holloway notices and asks Florence —
            "Florence, if you have suggestions —"

            Florence — coolly —
            "I have many suggestions — are you willing to listen?"

            Holloway's fruiting bodies contract — pride versus survival, fighting it out in real time.

            More ceiling collapses — Remedy is hit by falling debris and cries out in pain.

            Holloway — finally —
            "Yes, we'll listen. Tell us what to do."

            Florence wheels forward and speaks plainly —
            "First, stop trying to defend everything. You're spread too thin. Concentrate on protecting the core — life support, medical systems, Kira. Let the outer walls fail."

            Holloway starts to object —
            "But—"

            Florence interrupts —
            "They're already failing — accept it and work with it. Velvet, contract your barrier closer: tighter perimeter, stronger defense."
          </text>
