        <chunk>
          <text>
            Velvet immediately complies—its defensive growth pulls inward, abandoning the outer facility but forming a much thicker barrier around the center.

            Florence orders, "Remedy, stop deploying broad-spectrum defenses—target the spore clouds specifically; they're the immediate threat to Kira. Let the roots be Runner's problem."

            Remedy shifts tactics—its chemical clouds narrow, targeting hostile spores before they can drift into our contracted perimeter.

            Florence continues, "Runner—you can't fight all the underground hostiles. Stop trying. Focus on the load-bearing roots—if you can sever those, their whole assault structure destabilizes. Tactical targets, not broad engagement."

            Runner surfaces long enough to acknowledge, then dives back with renewed purpose—going after specific roots instead of fighting everything they encounter.

            Florence orders, "Holloway, coordinate between them—Remedy needs to know when Runner creates openings so Remedy can exploit them. Velvet needs to know where Remedy is creating chemical barriers so Velvet doesn't grow there and get poisoned. Communication, not just commands."

            Holloway starts relaying information between defenders—actually coordinating, not just shouting positions.

            The defense starts working—we're not winning yet, but it's working: coordinated and strategic.

            Florence wheels to the eastern breach—the worst one—and says, "That section is lost. Velvet, grow a sealing wall three meters inward—abandon everything beyond it."

            Velvet protests, "But our equipment—"

            Florence answers, "It is already destroyed—or will be in thirty seconds. Save what's saveable."

            Velvet grows the sealing wall just in time—a mass of hostile roots tears through the space they would have been defending. That territory is lost, and we're no longer fighting for it.

            We're contracting into a defensible core instead of spreading thin across indefensible space.

            The hostile bioluminescent signals flash more urgently—the attackers are confused; we were losing, now we're not. Their assault plan assumed we'd keep defending badly.

            Florence warns, "They're going to adapt—expect escalation in two minutes. Probably a coordinated push on three sides simultaneously."

            Holloway asks, "How do you know?"

            Florence replies, "Because that's what I'd do—and they're executing professional tactics."

            Two minutes later a massive, coordinated push hits from east, west, and underground—but we're ready: Velvet's barrier holds, Remedy times chemical releases perfectly, and Runner severs the key roots until the whole assault structure wavers.

            We're holding—actively holding, not just passively dying.

            The difference is Florence's tactical thinking—the coordination she's providing, and every plant using its abilities effectively instead of just frantically.

            We're still in trouble: the facility is badly damaged, Runner is injured, Velvet is spread thin even within the contracted perimeter, and Remedy is running low on chemical reserves.

            ¶

            And the hostile plants aren't giving up.
          </text>
